ushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England","Rushmere, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brewster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewestere</i>, <i>browestere</i> ‘(female) brewer’ (from Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). <i>Brewer</i> is the usual term in southern England, while <i>Brewster</i> is mainly midland, northern, and Scottish.","History: The <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrim William Brewster (1567–1644) was the son of the bailiff of the manor of Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, home of one of the earliest Puritan congregations. He was a prominent leader in Plymouth Colony from the 1620s until his death."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."]},{"name":"Bruster","meanings":["English: variant of   Brewster  .","Swiss German: variant of the topographic name   Brust   2, the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Brewster III was born in 1325, in Rushmere, Suffolk, England as the son of Sir John KS Brewster II. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1379, in Rushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England, at the age of 54, and was buried in Rushmere, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1325–1379":"1325–1379","1380–1410":"1380–1410","1299–1325":"1299–1325","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England","Rushmere, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1325–1379":"1325–1379","1380–1410":"1380–1410","1299–1325":"1299–1325","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere St Andrew, Suffolk, England","Rushmere, Suffolk, Englan